        <div class=3D"top_content">
      <h2><img src=3D"https://thinkreliability.com/hubfs/ThinkReliability_M=
arch2024/images/04-How-to-read-a-Cause-Map-Icon-1.png" alt=3D"How to read a=
 Cause Map">How to read a Cause Map=E2=84=A2<br><span>- - - - - - - - - -</=
span></h2>
<p>Start on the left. Read to the right saying =E2=80=9Cwas caused by=E2=80=
=9D in place of the arrows. Investigating a problem begins with the problem=
 and then backs into the causes by asking <i>Why</i> questions. The questio=
ns begin, =E2=80=9CWhy did this effect happen?=E2=80=9D The response to thi=
s question provides a cause (or causes), which is written down to the right=
.</p>
<p><img style=3D"float: none; margin: 10px auto; display: block;" src=3D"ht=
tps://thinkreliability.com/hs-fs/hubfs/ThinkReliability_March2024/images/ho=
w-to-read-a-causemap-new-1.png?width=3D1079&amp;height=3D146&amp;name=3Dhow=
-to-read-a-causemap-new-1.png" width=3D"1079" height=3D"146" alt=3D"how-to-=
read-a-causemap-new"></p>
<p>The next question is again, =E2=80=9CWhy did this effect happen?=E2=80=
=9D The cause that was written down last becomes the effect for the next <i=
>Why</i> question. Anyone who=E2=80=99s ever had a three-year-old in their =
life will immediately recognize how Why questions change a cause into an ef=
fect. This is fundamentally how causes and effects link together to create =
a chain of events. Writing down 5 <i>Whys</i>, as shown below, is a great w=
ay to start an investigation because it=E2=80=99s so simple.</p>
<p>In <em>Cause Mapping</em> root cause analysis, a problem within an organ=
ization is defined as a deviation from the ideal state. A <em>Cause Map</em=
> diagram always begins with this deviation, which is captured as the impac=
t to the organization=E2=80=99s overall goals.</p>
<p><img style=3D"float: none; margin: 10px auto; display: block;" alt=3D"ca=
use-mapping-goals" src=3D"https://thinkreliability.com/hubfs/ThinkReliabili=
ty_March2024/images/cause-mapping-goals.png"></p>
<p>In addition to the standard <i>Why</i> questions, which tend to create l=
inear cause-and-effect relationships, the <em>Cause Mapping</em> root&nbsp;=
 cause analysis also asks =E2=80=9CWhat was required to produce this effect=
?=E2=80=9D Anything that is required to produce an effect is a cause of tha=
t effect. This question, =E2=80=9CWhat was required?,=E2=80=9D allows you t=
o build a detailed <em>Cause Map</em> diagram that provides a more complete=
 representation of the actual issue.</p>
