        <div class=3D"top_content">
      <h2><img src=3D"https://thinkreliability.com/hubfs/ThinkReliability_M=
arch2024/images/05-Why-does-the-Cause-Map-read-left-to-right-Icon.png" alt=
=3D"Why does the Cause Map read left to right">Why does the Cause Map=E2=84=
=A2 diagram read left to right?<br><span>- - - - - - - - - -</span></h2>
<p>It should be noted that the popular fishbone cause-and-effect diagram st=
arts with the problem on the right and builds the causes to the left. It wa=
s created by Kaoru Ishikawa (1915-1989) in Japan. The fishbone diagram buil=
ds from right to left because the Japanese language reads from right to lef=
t. <em>Cause Mapping</em> root cause analysis actually uses Ishikawa=E2=80=
=99s convention by asking <i>Why</i> questions in the direction we read. Th=
e fishbone is widely recognized as one of the standard quality tools. Ishik=
awa was a pioneer with his approach. The fishbone cause-and-effect diagram =
is part of every Six Sigma program. A <em>Cause Map</em> diagram builds on =
the original lessons with the fishbone with some subtle but important disti=
nctions.</p>
<h3>How does the Cause Map=E2=84=A2 diagram differ from the fishbone approa=
ch?</h3>
<p><img style=3D"width: 484px; height: 247px; float: right; margin: 10px 0p=
x 0px 30px;" src=3D"https://thinkreliability.com/hubfs/ThinkReliability_Mar=
ch2024/images/RCABasics-09-Fishbone.jpg" alt=3D"RCABasics-09-Fishbone">A fi=
shbone starts with just one, single problem, which doesn=E2=80=99t reflect =
the nature of real-world issues. It reads right to left because the Japanes=
e language reads that direction. It mixes causes and possible causes withou=
t specifying evidence. And, it breaks apart the fundamental cause-and-effec=
t relationships within an issue by grouping the causes into general categor=
ies.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3>5-Whys on a Cause Map=E2=84=A2 diagram</h3>
<p>The 5-Why approach is an excellent example of basic cause-and-effect ana=
lysis. Just as a journey of a thousand miles begins with the first step, ev=
ery investigation, regardless of size, begins with one <i>Why</i> question.=
 The <i>Why</i> questions then continue, passing through five, until enough=
 <i>Why</i> questions have been asked (and answered) to sufficiently explai=
n the incident. The 5-Why approach, created by Sakichi Toyoda (1867 =E2=80=
=93 1930), the founder of Toyota, is a simple way to begin any investigatio=
n. A <em>Cause Map</em> diagram can start with just one <i>Why</i> question=
 and then expand to accommodate as many <i>Why</i> questions as necessary. =
Some refer to <em>Cause Mapping</em> root cause analysis as =E2=80=9C5-Whys=
 on Steroids.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p><img style=3D"margin: 10px auto; margin-bottom: 0;" src=3D"https://think=
reliability.com/hubfs/ThinkReliability_March2024/images/initial5whys.png" a=
lt=3D"initial5whys"></p>
<h3>Some causes are linked with =E2=80=9CAND=E2=80=9D in between</h3>
<p><img style=3D"width: 287px; height: 203.77px; float: right; margin: 10px=
 0px 0px 30px;" src=3D"https://thinkreliability.com/hubfs/ThinkReliability_=
March2024/images/Effect-cause-cause-image.jpg" alt=3D"effect cause">ANDs sh=
ow where more than one cause is required. When an effect has more than one =
cause, both causes are placed on the <em>Cause Map</em> diagram. Each cause=
 is connected to the effect with AND placed in between. These causes are in=
dependent of each other, but they are both required to produce that effect.=
 An AND is needed when people provide different, yet valid, explanations of=
 a cause. People think of cause-and-effect as a simple one-to-one relations=
hip: an effect has a cause. In reality, every effect has causes.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
